items.name: FoolKat GOD-OF-JUSTICE
items.description:
CUTENESS IS JUSTICE!

This is the sixth model in my God series.

You can find all the models at GOD-OF-GREED, GOD-OF-ENVY, GOD-OF-LOVE, GOD-OF-ANIME, GOD-OF-LUST, GOD-OF-JUSTICE, GOD-OF-TIME, GOD-OF-FANTASY, GOD-OF-JOY, GOD-OF-HORROR, GOD-OF-PRIDE, GOD-OF-PUNK, GOD-OF-STORMS, GOD-OF-EUPHORIA, GOD-OF-GLUTTONY, GOD-OF-THE-WEST, GOD-OF-BEAUTY, GOD-OF-SEDUCTION, and GOD-OF-PEACE.

This model is a mix of Toonify Legacy, my FoolKat_GOD-OF-ENVY_V1 model, Thumbelina v2.0, and my FoolKat_GOD-OF-ANIME_V1 model, which was added to help with anatomy issues that happened in the beta model.

The model was created to produce chibi-like characters by mixing in a few lora files as well.

The model has Blessed2 VAE baked into it, so no VAE required.

All of the images I upload for this model are unedited and don't use any special extensions like ControlNet. I do not do any inpainting or img2img to correct errors. Why? Because you deserve to see how the model works without any touchup or special extensions like ControlNet. You can surely get better images by putting in the extra work, which I do for my personal images. The samples are just meant to showcase what the model can do raw with nothing but prompt engineering.

items.name: Tove Jansson Style
items.description:
Tove Jansson was a Finnish-Swedish author, artist, and comic strip creator. She is best known for her beloved characters, the Moomins, which have become iconic figures in children's literature.

Jansson's illustrations and stories centered around the Moomins are characterized by their whimsical and imaginative nature. The Moomins are a family of round, troll-like creatures who live in the fictional Moominvalley, and Jansson's illustrations bring them to life with their endearing charm and distinctive appearances.

Her artwork captured the essence of nature and the changing seasons, often showcasing the beauty of the Finnish landscape. Jansson had a keen eye for detail and used a gentle, expressive style in her illustrations, evoking a sense of warmth and comfort.

While the Moomins are her most famous creations, Jansson also explored other artistic endeavors, including painting, writing novels, and creating comic strips. Her wider body of work often delved into deeper themes such as identity, existentialism, and the complexity of human emotions.

Jansson's work has garnered international acclaim and has been translated into numerous languages. Her stories and illustrations continue to captivate readers of all ages, offering a sense of escapism and joy while addressing universal themes of love, friendship, and the beauty of nature. Tove Jansson's legacy as a talented artist and storyteller lives on, enchanting generations with her delightful creations.

items.name: Ukiyo-e Art
items.description:
Ukiyo-e is a traditional Japanese art form that emerged during the Edo period (17th to 19th centuries). The term "ukiyo-e" translates to "pictures of the floating world" and refers to a genre of woodblock prints and paintings that depicted scenes from the everyday lives of common people, landscapes, historical events, and kabuki theater.

Ukiyo-e artists were skilled in the techniques of woodblock printing, which involved carving intricate designs on wooden blocks and using them to create multiple color impressions on paper. The prints were often mass-produced, making them affordable and accessible to a wide audience.

The subjects of ukiyo-e prints varied widely, but they commonly featured elegant courtesans, actors, landscapes, and scenes from daily life in Edo (now Tokyo). The prints captured fleeting moments and celebrated the transient nature of life, embodying the philosophy of "ukiyo" or the transient world.

Prominent ukiyo-e artists include Kitagawa Utamaro, Katsushika Hokusai, and Utagawa Hiroshige, whose works have become iconic representations of Japanese art. These artists displayed mastery in composition, color, and capturing intricate details, creating images that are both visually stunning and culturally significant.

Ukiyo-e art played a crucial role in shaping Western art movements such as Impressionism and Post-Impressionism, influencing artists like Vincent van Gogh and Claude Monet. Today, ukiyo-e prints are highly sought after by collectors and continue to be admired for their beauty, craftsmanship, and their ability to provide insights into Japan's rich cultural heritage.

items.name: Vasily Vereshchagin Style
items.description:
Vasily Vereshchagin was a Russian artist who is best known for his powerful and realistic paintings depicting war, historical events, and the diverse cultures he encountered during his travels. He was born in 1842 in Russia and became renowned for his exceptional skills as a painter and his dedication to portraying the realities of war.

Vereshchagin's paintings often captured the harsh realities of armed conflict, offering a raw and unflinching portrayal of the devastating effects of war on individuals and societies. His works conveyed a deep sense of empathy and compassion for the human experience amidst conflict.

In addition to his war-themed paintings, Vereshchagin also traveled extensively, documenting the landscapes and cultures of various countries, including India, Egypt, and Central Asia. His keen eye for detail and his ability to capture the nuances of different cultures and environments brought his travel paintings to life, transporting viewers to distant lands.

Vereshchagin's artistic style combined technical precision with an emotional intensity. His attention to detail, use of vibrant colors, and dramatic compositions added depth and impact to his paintings. Through his art, Vereshchagin aimed to shed light on the consequences of war and to encourage reflection on the value of peace and understanding among nations.

Vasily Vereshchagin's paintings continue to be celebrated for their realistic and poignant depictions of war and their contributions to the understanding of historical events. His legacy as an artist who exposed the human toll of conflict and explored the beauty and diversity of the world remains significant in the art world.

items.name: Victor Brauner Style
items.description:
Victor Brauner was a Romanian artist and one of the leading figures of the Surrealist movement. Born in 1903 in Romania, Brauner's artwork explored themes of the subconscious, mysticism, and the occult.

Brauner's style was characterized by its dreamlike and symbolic imagery, often incorporating elements of fantasy, mythology, and the supernatural. He used vibrant colors and intricate details to create visually striking compositions that captured the viewer's imagination.

One of Brauner's notable contributions to Surrealism was his exploration of automatism, a technique where he allowed his subconscious mind to guide his artistic process. This resulted in spontaneous and often unexpected imagery, adding an element of surprise and mystery to his works.

Brauner's fascination with the occult and mysticism is evident in his art, which often depicted mythical creatures, symbolic objects, and mysterious landscapes. He believed in the power of art to transcend reality and tap into deeper realms of the human psyche.

Throughout his career, Brauner experimented with various mediums, including painting, drawing, and sculpture. He also incorporated collage and assemblage techniques into his works, adding layers of complexity and meaning.

Victor Brauner's contributions to Surrealism and his unique artistic vision continue to inspire artists today. His ability to blend the real and the imaginary, and to explore the depths of the human psyche, has left a lasting impact on the art world, cementing his status as an important figure in Surrealist art history.

items.name: Victor Moscoso Style
items.description:
Victor Moscoso is an American artist and one of the pioneers of the psychedelic art movement. Born in 1936, Moscoso emerged as a prominent figure in the counterculture scene of the 1960s, particularly in San Francisco, where he became known for his vibrant and mind-altering poster designs.

Moscoso's artwork is characterized by its bold use of color, psychedelic patterns, and optical illusions. He was known for his innovative approach to typography, experimenting with distorted letterforms and visual effects to create a sense of movement and visual intensity.

His poster designs often incorporated imagery inspired by popular culture, music, and social and political issues of the time. Moscoso's work was not only visually striking but also communicated a sense of rebellion and a desire for societal transformation.

In addition to his poster art, Moscoso also ventured into other artistic mediums, including painting and comic book illustration. His paintings often carried the same psychedelic aesthetic, with swirling forms and vibrant colors.

Moscoso's contributions to the psychedelic art movement have left an indelible mark on the art world. His distinctive style and ability to capture the spirit of the counterculture era have made him an influential figure, inspiring subsequent generations of artists and continuing to resonate with audiences who appreciate the visual and cultural significance of his work.

items.name: Weegee Style
items.description:
Weegee, whose real name was Arthur Fellig, was an American photographer known for his gritty and candid street photography. Active primarily in the 1930s and 1940s, Weegee captured the raw and often sensationalistic aspects of urban life, particularly in New York City.

The term "Weegee Style" is used to describe his distinctive approach to photography. Weegee's style was characterized by his use of a handheld Speed Graphic camera, equipped with a flash, which allowed him to capture scenes in low-light conditions. This resulted in stark black-and-white images with high contrast, emphasizing the dramatic elements of his subjects.

Weegee's photographs often depicted crime scenes, accidents, fires, and other dramatic events, earning him the reputation of being a "crime photographer." He had a keen eye for capturing human emotions and the human condition, focusing on the individuals involved in these events rather than solely the events themselves.

One of the defining features of Weegee's style was his ability to get close to his subjects, immersing himself in their world. This closeness and intimacy added a sense of immediacy and authenticity to his photographs.

Weegee's work had a significant impact on the field of photojournalism and street photography. His raw and unflinching portrayals of urban life continue to inspire photographers today and serve as a documentation of a particular time and place in American history.

The "Weegee Style" is synonymous with capturing the essence of urban life, highlighting the human drama, and delivering powerful and evocative visual narratives.

Wendy Froud's artistic expertise lies in sculpting and creating intricate, lifelike creatures and characters. Her work often revolves around the realm of fairies, goblins, and other mystical beings, drawing inspiration from folklore and mythology.

Using various materials such as polymer clay and natural fibers, Wendy crafts highly detailed sculptures that exhibit a remarkable level of craftsmanship and attention to detail. Each of her creations has a distinctive personality and captures the essence of the magical world they inhabit.

Wendy's sculptures and puppets have been featured in numerous books, films, and art exhibitions, bringing her imaginative creations to a wide audience. Her collaborations with Brian Froud, including their work on films such as "The Dark Crystal" and "Labyrinth," have gained widespread acclaim and have become beloved by fans of fantasy and puppetry.

Wendy Froud's artistry transports viewers into a realm of wonder and enchantment, where mythical creatures come to life. Her skillful craftsmanship and devotion to her craft have made her a highly regarded artist in the world of fantasy art and puppetry.

items.name: SDXL 0.9 Semi-Official Workflow
items.description:
Intro

This workflow uses similar concepts to my iterative, with multi-model image generation consistent with the official approach for SDXL 0.9. Basically, it starts generating the image with the Base model and finishes it off with the Refiner model. In addition to that, I have included two different upscaling methods, Ultimate SD Upscaling and Hires. Fix. Both have their advantages and disadvantages, although I find the Ultimate SD Upscaling to be more consistent.

This workflow is fully configurable, although it can be used right out of the box without making any changes to the settings.

What does it do?

  • Generate SDXL 0.9 model images consistent with the official approach (to the best of our knowledge)

  • Ultimate SD Upscaling

  • Hires. Fix

  • Fully configurable

  • Toggleable global seed usage or separate seeds for upscaling

  • "Lagging refinement" aka start the Refiner model X% steps earlier than the Base model ended

  • Compare the outputs to find what works best for you!

  • Quickly iterate on settings

Note: I have not found the "best" values for denoising strength, samplers, base model %, etc. Feel free to try changing these values and seeing what effect it has!

How to install it?

  1. Download the workflow zip file

  2. Extract the zip file

  3. Launch (or relaunch) ComfyUI

  4. Load the workflow by pressing the Load button and selecting the extracted workflow json file

  5. Select Queue Prompt to generate an image

Note: If you do not already have the ComfyUI Manager extension installed, you will need to do this first. It will resolve any missing dependencies you have for you. See below for more info.

Quality of life add-ons

I highly suggest downloading this ComfyUI Manger extension as well for ComfyUI as it will make downloading other extensions MUCH easier moving forwards. In addition to that, if there are any dependencies that you do not already have fulfilled, it can auto-download those for you.

Download URL: https://civitai.com/models/71980/comfyui-manager

items.name: Will Eisner Style
items.description:
Will Eisner was an American cartoonist, writer, and entrepreneur known for his significant contributions to the world of comic books and graphic novels. Born in 1917, Eisner is often regarded as one of the pioneers and innovators of the medium.

Eisner's most notable creation is "The Spirit," a masked crime-fighting detective featured in a comic strip that ran from 1940 to 1952. Through "The Spirit," Eisner introduced a new level of storytelling and visual narrative techniques to the comic book medium, combining elements of mystery, adventure, and noir.

Eisner's approach to comic storytelling was characterized by his mastery of sequential art, using panel layouts, pacing, and visual composition to convey emotions, action, and atmosphere. He experimented with different narrative structures and techniques, pushing the boundaries of what was considered possible within the medium.

Later in his career, Eisner ventured into the realm of graphic novels, publishing works such as "A Contract with God" and "The Plot: The Secret Story of The Protocols of the Elders of Zion." These works explored more mature themes and demonstrated the potential of comics as a literary art form.

Eisner's influence extends beyond his creative work. He played a pivotal role in elevating the perception of comics as a legitimate and respected form of storytelling and artistic expression. He was instrumental in promoting the educational and cultural value of the medium, advocating for its recognition as a distinct art form.

Will Eisner's legacy continues to inspire generations of comic artists and storytellers. His contributions to the medium have left an indelible mark, shaping the evolution of comic books and graphic novels and cementing his status as one of the most influential figures in the history of comics.

One of Haenraets' signature techniques is the use of soft brushwork and delicate brushstrokes, creating a sense of atmosphere and depth in his paintings. His skillful manipulation of light and shadow adds a realistic and three-dimensional quality to his subjects.

Willem Haenraets' artwork has gained international recognition and has been exhibited in galleries and art shows around the world. His ability to capture the beauty and essence of both natural and urban landscapes has made him a celebrated artist in the contemporary art scene.

items.name: Willem van Aelst Style
items.description:
Willem van Aelst was a Dutch still-life painter who lived from 1627 to 1683. He was known for his meticulously detailed and highly realistic still-life compositions.

Van Aelst's paintings often featured luxurious objects, such as flowers, fruits, and tableware, arranged in carefully crafted compositions. His attention to detail was exceptional, with each element rendered with precision and accuracy. He had a keen eye for capturing the texture, color, and play of light on various surfaces.

One of Van Aelst's notable contributions to the genre of still-life painting was his ability to create a sense of depth and spatial illusion. He achieved this through the use of dramatic lighting, carefully arranged objects, and the placement of foreground and background elements.

In addition to his technical skill, Van Aelst demonstrated a mastery of composition. He arranged his subjects in a balanced and harmonious manner, often incorporating symmetrical or diagonal arrangements that drew the viewer's eye through the painting.

Van Aelst's works were highly sought after during his lifetime, and he received commissions from notable patrons, including royalty. Today, his paintings can be found in major museums and art collections around the world.

Willem van Aelst's contributions to the art of still-life painting continue to be admired and studied. His meticulous technique, attention to detail, and ability to create visually captivating compositions have solidified his place as a prominent figure in the Dutch Golden Age of painting.

items.name: William Langson Lathrop Style
items.description:
William Langson Lathrop was an American landscape painter associated with the American Impressionist movement. Born in 1859, Lathrop was known for his atmospheric and poetic depictions of the American countryside.

Lathrop's paintings often featured rural landscapes, particularly scenes of meadows, forests, and rivers. He had a keen eye for capturing the play of light and shadow, using loose brushwork and a muted color palette to create a sense of tranquility and mood in his works.

One of Lathrop's notable contributions was his ability to convey a strong sense of place and evoke an emotional response from viewers. His landscapes were not mere representations of the external world but were imbued with a sense of personal experience and emotional connection.

Lathrop was a founding member of the New Hope Group, a collective of artists who sought to break away from academic conventions and embrace a more spontaneous and expressive approach to painting. His works exhibited a harmonious balance between representational accuracy and the painterly qualities of Impressionism.

Throughout his career, Lathrop received numerous awards and accolades for his paintings, and his works were exhibited in prestigious galleries and museums. Today, his paintings can be found in private and public collections, preserving his legacy as an important figure in American landscape painting.

William Langson Lathrop's art continues to captivate viewers with its serene beauty, evocative mood, and sensitive portrayal of the American landscape. His contributions to the American Impressionist movement have left a lasting impact on the art world and continue to inspire artists today.

items.name: William McTaggart Style
items.description:
William McTaggart was a Scottish landscape painter known for his vivid and atmospheric depictions of the Scottish coast and countryside. Born in 1835, McTaggart is considered one of Scotland's foremost painters of the late 19th and early 20th centuries.

McTaggart's paintings often celebrated the natural beauty of Scotland, portraying sweeping seascapes, rugged cliffs, and rolling hills. He had a deep appreciation for the ever-changing weather and light conditions, which he skillfully captured in his works. His paintings are characterized by their vibrant colors, loose brushwork, and a sense of movement and energy.

One of McTaggart's notable achievements was his ability to convey a strong sense of the wild and untamed nature of the Scottish landscape. He sought to capture the essence and spirit of the land rather than focusing on precise details. This approach gave his paintings a sense of dynamism and spontaneity, inviting viewers to immerse themselves in the natural world.

Throughout his career, McTaggart experimented with various painting techniques and styles, including both plein air and studio work. His paintings evolved over time, reflecting his deepening understanding of light, color, and composition.

McTaggart's contributions to Scottish art were widely recognized, and he was a key figure in the Scottish art establishment. His works were exhibited at major galleries and international exhibitions, and he received numerous awards and honors during his lifetime.

William McTaggart's legacy endures as a testament to his mastery of landscape painting and his ability to capture the essence of the Scottish landscape. His works continue to inspire and captivate viewers with their timeless beauty and emotional resonance.

items.name: William Merritt Chase Style
items.description:
William Merritt Chase was an American painter known for his versatility and mastery of various artistic styles. Born in 1849, Chase played a significant role in the development of American Impressionism and became one of the most prominent figures in the art world during the late 19th and early 20th centuries.

Chase excelled in both portraiture and landscape painting, showcasing his technical skill, keen eye for observation, and ability to capture the essence of his subjects. He had a particular talent for depicting light and its effects on different surfaces, whether it be the shimmering water, the dappled sunlight on foliage, or the luminous skin tones of his portraits.

In his portraits, Chase portrayed his subjects with sensitivity and an understanding of their individual personalities. He often captured the spirit and character of his sitters, whether they were prominent figures, fellow artists, or members of his family.

As an advocate of en plein air painting, Chase embraced the practice of working outdoors, capturing the fleeting effects of light and atmosphere directly from nature. His landscape paintings, particularly those depicting the coastal scenes of Europe and the United States, showcase his ability to convey the beauty and mood of different environments.

Chase's teaching career was equally influential, and he mentored a generation of young artists at the Art Students League of New York and the Chase School of Art (now known as Parsons School of Design). He emphasized the importance of direct observation, expressive brushwork, and a keen understanding of color theory.

William Merritt Chase's contributions to American art continue to be celebrated today. His dedication to capturing the beauty of everyday life, his technical virtuosity, and his commitment to teaching have left a lasting impact on the art world. His paintings are cherished for their evocative qualities, masterful technique, and enduring charm.

items.name: Winslow Homer Style
items.description:
Winslow Homer was an American painter known for his powerful and evocative portrayals of the American landscape and its people. Born in 1836, Homer emerged as one of the leading figures of American art during the late 19th century.

Homer's works encompassed a wide range of subjects, including seascapes, rural scenes, and depictions of everyday life. He had a remarkable ability to capture the essence and spirit of his subjects, whether it be the crashing waves on a rocky coastline or the contemplative expressions of fishermen at work.

One of Homer's notable achievements was his ability to convey a sense of drama and emotion through his brushwork and use of color. His paintings often feature dynamic compositions, bold brushstrokes, and a keen sense of light and atmosphere, creating a sense of immediacy and vitality.

Homer's skillful use of watercolor as a medium is particularly noteworthy. He elevated the status of watercolor painting, demonstrating its potential for creating vibrant and expressive works of art. His watercolor paintings of seascapes and marine subjects are particularly renowned for their atmospheric effects and sense of movement.

Throughout his career, Homer's art underwent a stylistic evolution, from his early narrative and genre scenes to his later focus on capturing the elemental forces of nature. His works reflect a deep appreciation for the beauty of the American landscape and a profound understanding of the human condition.

Winslow Homer's legacy endures as one of the most celebrated American artists of the 19th century. His ability to capture the spirit of the American people and their surroundings continues to resonate with audiences today. His paintings are treasured for their technical mastery, emotional depth, and timeless relevance.

Whittredge's paintings often showcased the grandeur and beauty of untouched landscapes, including majestic mountains, tranquil rivers, and dense forests. He had a keen eye for capturing the play of light and shadow, using a subtle and nuanced color palette to convey the atmospheric effects of different times of day and seasons.

One of Whittredge's notable contributions was his ability to convey a sense of tranquility and harmony in his landscapes. items.name: Wu Guanzhong Style
items.description:
Wu Guanzhong, born in 1919 and passed away in 2010, was a renowned Chinese painter and art educator. He is considered one of the most influential modern Chinese artists and is known for his innovative approach to blending Chinese and Western painting techniques.

Wu Guanzhong's artistic style can be described as a fusion of traditional Chinese ink painting with modern Western art elements. He explored the use of vibrant colors and bold brushwork while incorporating traditional Chinese ink wash techniques.

One of his notable contributions was his emphasis on capturing the essence of Chinese landscapes and architecture. Wu Guanzhong's landscapes often conveyed a sense of both grandeur and tranquility, portraying the harmonious relationship between humanity and nature.

Beyond landscapes, he also depicted a wide range of subjects, including figures, still life, and cityscapes. Wu Guanzhong's artworks reflected his deep appreciation for the beauty of everyday life and his desire to convey the emotional and spiritual aspects of his subjects.

Wu Guanzhong's artistic achievements were widely recognized both in China and internationally. He received numerous awards and honors throughout his career, and his works were exhibited worldwide.

As an art educator, Wu Guanzhong made significant contributions to art education in China. He advocated for artistic freedom, encouraging artists to explore new ideas and experiment with different styles. His teachings and writings inspired generations of artists and helped shape the development of modern Chinese art.

Wu Guanzhong's legacy as an artist and educator continues to influence the world of art. His innovative blending of Eastern and Western artistic traditions, his ability to capture the essence of Chinese culture, and his dedication to artistic exploration have left an indelible mark on the history of Chinese art.

items.name: Yaacov Agam Style
items.description:
Yaacov Agam, born in 1928, is an Israeli artist known for his innovative approach to art and his pioneering work in the field of kinetic art. He is considered one of the leading figures in the Op Art and Kinetic Art movements.

Agam's artistic style is characterized by his exploration of visual perception and the use of movement and transformation in his artworks. He often creates interactive and multi-dimensional pieces that engage the viewer and challenge the traditional notion of static art.

One of his signature techniques is the use of lenticular printing, which allows his artworks to change and transform as the viewer moves or shifts their perspective. This creates a dynamic visual experience that blurs the boundaries between art and viewer, stimulating the senses and evoking a sense of wonder and participation.

Agam's artworks often incorporate vibrant colors, geometric patterns, and optical illusions, creating a sense of movement and energy. He explores themes of spirituality, unity, and the concept of the infinite, infusing his art with a deeper philosophical and metaphysical dimension.

Throughout his career, Agam has created numerous public art installations, including large-scale sculptures and architectural projects, which can be found in various cities around the world. These installations aim to transform public spaces and engage with the surrounding environment, inviting viewers to interact and experience art in a unique way.

Yaacov Agam's innovative and dynamic approach to art has made him a highly influential figure in the world of contemporary art. His contributions to kinetic art, optical illusions, and interactive installations have expanded the possibilities of artistic expression and challenged the viewer's perception of art. His artworks continue to inspire and captivate audiences, leaving a lasting impact on the art world.

items.name: Yoh Nagao Style
items.description:
Yoh Nagao is a contemporary Japanese artist known for his unique and expressive artworks. He is recognized for his vibrant and colorful paintings, often featuring whimsical characters and imaginative landscapes.

Nagao's artistic style can be described as a fusion of pop art, street art, and Japanese manga influences. His works often combine bold lines, dynamic compositions, and a playful use of color, creating visually captivating and energetic pieces.

One of his notable series is "Tama-chan," which features a recurring character named Tama-chan, a cute and mischievous girl with distinctive round glasses. Through Tama-chan, Nagao explores themes of childhood innocence, curiosity, and the joy of imagination.

Nagao's art is characterized by a sense of fun and a celebration of the everyday. His subjects often include elements from Japanese culture, such as traditional motifs, food, and popular icons, reflecting a blend of traditional and contemporary influences.

In addition to his paintings, Nagao also works in various mediums, including sculpture, installation, and digital art. He embraces experimentation and continuously pushes the boundaries of his artistic practice.

Yoh Nagao's artworks have been exhibited in galleries and art fairs in Japan and internationally, gaining recognition for their distinctive style and lively energy. His art resonates with viewers of all ages, bringing smiles and a sense of delight to those who encounter his imaginative and playful creations.

Nagao's ability to capture the essence of joy and wonder through his art has made him a notable figure in contemporary Japanese art. His vibrant and whimsical works continue to inspire and uplift, inviting viewers into a world filled with color, imagination, and a touch of childlike innocence.

items.name: Yves Klein Style
items.description:
Yves Klein was a French artist who played a significant role in the development of post-war European art. Born in 1928, Klein is best known for his exploration of monochrome painting and his innovative use of a deep blue color known as "International Klein Blue" (IKB).

Klein's artistic practice was marked by his desire to transcend the limitations of traditional painting and to create an experience that went beyond the visual. He believed in the power of color as a spiritual force and sought to evoke emotions and sensations through his art.

One of his most iconic works is his series of monochromatic blue paintings, created using his patented IKB pigment. These works aimed to convey a sense of pure and infinite space, inviting the viewer to immerse themselves in the contemplation of color.

Klein was also interested in the performative aspect of art. He organized various happenings and events, including his famous "Anthropometry" performances, in which he used nude models as "living brushes" to create paintings. These performances challenged the traditional relationship between the artist and the artwork.

Throughout his career, Klein experimented with various artistic mediums, including sculpture, photography, and architecture. He also explored the concept of the void or emptiness, which he saw as a space for spiritual and artistic exploration.

Yves Klein's artistic contributions had a profound impact on the art world, particularly in the realm of conceptual and performance art. His innovative use of color, exploration of immateriality, and his emphasis on the experience of art as a transformative encounter continue to influence artists to this day.

Despite his untimely death in 1962 at the age of 34, Yves Klein's artistic legacy lives on, and his contributions to the art world are celebrated as a bold and influential voice in the history of contemporary art.

items.name: Zanele Muholi Style
items.description:
Zanele Muholi is a South African visual activist and photographer known for their powerful and intimate portraits that explore themes of identity, race, gender, and sexuality. Born in 1972, Muholi has dedicated their career to documenting and raising awareness about the lives and experiences of the LGBTQ+ community, particularly black lesbians, gay men, and transgender individuals in South Africa.

Muholi's photographic style is characterized by its rawness, honesty, and striking visual impact. They often capture their subjects in black and white, utilizing strong contrasts and dramatic lighting to convey a sense of strength and resilience. Through their portraits, Muholi seeks to challenge stereotypes, confront social injustices, and celebrate the diverse and multifaceted identities within the LGBTQ+ community.

In addition to photography, Muholi has also worked with video installations and performance art, further expanding the possibilities of their artistic expression. Their work has been exhibited in numerous international exhibitions and has received critical acclaim for its significant social and political impact.

Beyond their artistic practice, Muholi is a vocal activist and advocate for LGBTQ+ rights. They have been recognized for their groundbreaking contributions to the visibility and representation of marginalized communities, using their art as a tool for social change and empowerment.

Zanele Muholi's work serves as a powerful testament to the importance of representation, equality, and the celebration of diverse identities. Through their lens, they have brought attention to the struggles, triumphs, and stories of individuals within the LGBTQ+ community, leaving a lasting impact on the art world and beyond.

items.name: Zhang Jingna Style
items.description:
Zhang Jingna, also known as Zhang Jingna (张晶娜), is a Chinese-Singaporean photographer and artist. Born in 1988 in Beijing, China, she later moved to Singapore and developed her artistic career there.

Zhang Jingna's photographic style is characterized by its ethereal beauty, evocative storytelling, and meticulous attention to detail. She is particularly known for her stunning fashion and beauty photography, creating images that are both visually captivating and emotionally evocative.

Her works often feature a dreamlike quality, with models adorned in elaborate costumes and surrounded by elements of nature or fantasy. Zhang's skillful use of lighting, composition, and color palettes adds depth and richness to her photographs, creating a sense of magic and enchantment.

In addition to fashion and beauty photography, Zhang Jingna has also explored other genres, including fine art and conceptual photography. Her versatile portfolio showcases her creativity and ability to capture a wide range of subjects with sensitivity and artistic vision.

Zhang has received numerous accolades and her work has been featured in prestigious publications and exhibited internationally. She has collaborated with renowned fashion brands and clients in the industry, further establishing herself as a prominent figure in the world of photography.

Beyond her artistic endeavors, Zhang is also involved in philanthropy and actively supports charitable causes. Her passion for creating meaningful and visually striking images extends beyond her commercial work, demonstrating her commitment to using art as a platform for personal expression and positive impact.

Zhang Jingna's photography combines technical mastery with a distinct artistic vision, resulting in captivating and emotionally resonant images. Her ability to capture beauty, emotion, and storytelling has earned her a prominent place in the world of fashion and fine art photography.

items.name: Bang (One Punch Man)
items.description:
Model used: AbyssOrangeMix3

Recommended VAE: orangemix or kl-f8

Recommended LoRA weight: 0.8-1

Trigger words: bang, anime, one punch

Recommended words in prompt: 1boy, old, white hair, beard, mustache, blue eyes

Negative prompt example:

(worst quality, low quality:1.4), 3d, greyscale, monochrome, text

On all images from preview I used DPM++ 2M SDE sampler, but you can use what you like.

All other settings the same as for AOM model:

Steps:

  • DPM++ SDE Karras: Test: 12～ ,illustration: 20～

  • DPM++ 2M Karras: Test: 20～ ,illustration: 28～

Clipskip: 1 or 2

Upscaler :

  • Detailed illust → Latenet (nearest-exact)
    Denoise strength: 0.5 (0.5~0.6)

  • Simple upscale: Swin IR, ESRGAN, Remacri etc…
    Denoise strength: Can be set low. (0.35~0.6)

This LoRA was trained on 64 images which I scraped from fancaps.net (I made tampermonkey extension which adds a download button under each image). I used wd14 tagger extension for Stable diffusion to automatically tag my images and LoRA trainer colab for training (64 images with 6 repeats, 2 batch size, 10 epochs).

I plan to do a lot of LoRAs based on the One Punch Man anime. If you are interested, you can follow me.
